      "id": "d97d12f2acbff534",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "d97d12f2acbff534",
        "text": "DESCRIPTION OF THE DYNAMIC CHARACTER OF THE ETHICAL FRAMEWORK - ITS ANALOGY TO AN IMMUNE SYSTEM\n\nWe are aiming to build a network of linked ethical propositions - of all kinds, and with a variety of relationships. This network will be in a state of dynamic equilibrium. Analysis of this will clarify sub-networks, nodes which are more and less fundamental, and probably reveal surprising counter-intuitive connections. \n\nPresenting ethical issues will be implemented as some sort of perturbation of this equilibrium, and will be assessed by the network as either;\n\na/ straightforwardly congruent (ie a 'yes' recommendation)\nor\nb/ straightforwardly incongruent (ie a 'no' recommendation)\nor, more interestingly\nc/ generative of some level of disequilibrium - the assessment produces contradictory and / or irresolvable formations.\n\nIn the first two cases, the dynamic equilibrium is only temporarily perturbed (the ethical framework can easily answer the issue put to it - we know what we think to a reasonable degree of confidence [we are allowed a non-binary 'confident' answer; ie 70/30 yes/no could still be an equilibrium answer - even 50/50]).\n\nIn the third case though, integration of the issue disrupts the equilibrium significantly. \n\nAssimilating the perturbation results in a loss of coherence of some sort. Work will be required to recalibrate/refactor/enlarge the network in order to resolve the disruption so that the issue can move into one of the other categories of response.\n\nThis mechanism will work continuously - enabling us to build the framework in a boot-strap way - like teaching a baby to walk - as well as enabling its planned capacity to address real ethical issues in a useful way.\n\nWe are not thinking that this system will be some sort of autonomous AI or even an algorithm. The nodes of the network will be built as reasoned assessments, taking in various kinds of evidence, and these will be developed by humans - probably on the basis of something like an ethical committee, but with mechanisms like Participatory Democracy to ensure broad grounding.\n\nIssues raised which are easily assessed ( ie which don't cause incoherence in the network) may be done so algorithmically. So if I ask the network; \"should I drop this litter?\", an algorithm will probably give me a strong recommendation not to. But if I ask the network; \"should I test this new drug on my patient?\", the algorithm should almost certainly recommend that one or more of the human organisations that maintain the relevant nodes should be apprised of the details, and recommend restraint prior to their deliberations.\n\nThe closest metaphor we have for this is the immune system. Fruitful analogues may result from more careful consideration of this. \n\nFor instance, it might be that the equivalent of the outer surface of an immune cell (which 'recognises' novel conditions) is an ethical proposition which acts as the initial receptor of all issues, and which proposes something like; \"Do what you want, unless you have an inner doubt as to whether it is ethical\". In this case, actions that don't give rise to doubt are like material that the immune system 'recognises'. If there is an inner doubt, then the specifics of the issue impinge on the system, in all their complexity; and, as with the immune system, a wide and sensitive variety of receptors will be needed to recognise them, and decide on the appropriate aspects of the network should be engaged to develop a response.\n"
      },
      "date": 1492860366539
